# Construct arrays for the anchor positions of the 3D bar plot.
histogram2d, xbins, ybins = np.histogram2d(a.ravel(),b.ravel(),[256,256],[[0,256],[0,256]])

xpos, ypos = np.meshgrid(xbins[:-1] + 0.25, ybins[:-1] + 0.25, indexing="ij")
xpos = xpos.ravel()
ypos = ypos.ravel()
zpos = 0

# Construct arrays with the dimensions for the bars.
dx = dy = 0.5 * np.ones_like(zpos)
dz = histogram2d.ravel()

fig = plt.figure()
axes = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
axes.bar3d(xpos, ypos, zpos, dx, dy, dz, zsort='average')
plt.show()

# Find the 2D histogram of roi using calcHist, which can be done with np.histogram2d also (as we did above).
hist_roi  = cv.calcHist([lab_roi],[1, 2], None, [256, 256], [0, 255, 0, 256])
# Normalize the 2D histogram.
cv.normalize(hist_roi, hist_roi, 0, 255, cv.NORM_MINMAX)

#Calculate the back projection of the 2D histogram.
dst = cv.calcBackProject([lab_img], [1,2], hist_roi, [0,256,0,256], 1)

# Convolute with circular disc and conbine the decentralized spot
disc = cv.getStructuringElement(cv.MORPH_ELLIPSE,(5,5))
dst = cv.filter2D(dst, -1, disc, dst)

# Get threshold and bit for finding roi in the original image.
ret, thresh = cv.threshold(dst, 50, 255, 0)

# Get the threshold image for 3 channels.
thr_img = cv.merge((thresh, thresh, thresh))

# Calculate with bits image.
res_img= cv.bitwise_and(img, thr_img)
res_img = cv.cvtColor(res_img, cv.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

# Stack the original image, threshold image, and result image together.
# To figure out the performance of finding the roi with back projection.
res_stacked = np.hstack((rgb_img, thr_img, res_img))

# Display the final production.
plt.imshow(res_stacked)
plt.title('Original, Threshold, and Result Images')
plt.show()

g. Evaluate the performance of these techniques with histograms (i.e. illustrate when it works, and when it does not work)

Answer:

  1. Spatial Derivatives help us find edges in horizontal and vertical directions. It works well when there are clear and distinct horizontal or vertical edges in the target image. And the resulted derivative image becomes blurry if there are not such edges.
  2. 2D histogram and back projection help us figure out the characters of a region of interest, thus we can search the target region in the original image（ROI）. It works well when the character of the ROI is unique in the target image. And the performance mainly depends on the color.
  3. The contrast limited adaptive histogram equalization helps us apply a histogram equalization on the L channel and enhance the contrast. It can also be used to enchance the contract of original image when we merge the converted L channel with a, b channels.

# The mean image plus the first p principal components as a reconstruction (p=10).
pca = PCA(n_components=10)
components = pca.fit_transform(images_five)
components = np.transpose(components)

coefficients = pca.singular_values_ 

test_image1 = coefficients[0] * components[0]
for i in range(1, len(components)):
    test_image1 = test_image1 + coefficients[i] * components[i]

test_image1 = test_image1.reshape((28, 28))
test_image1 = test_image1 + images_mean

plt.imshow(test_image1, cmap='gray')
plt.title('test_image1')
plt.show()

c. Read https://doi.org/10.1109/34.598227 ‘Probabilistic visual learning for object representation’ (PAMI1997). Compute and display a DFFS (distance-from feature-space) and SSD (sum-of-square-differences) heat maps for detection using your PCA representation of a MNIST number. For the test image, use a composite image made of MNIST test images (see example below).

In [31]:
# Calculate the DFFS image with the PCA representation (p=10)

# For simplicity, we do not apply padding operation on the composite image.
#eigenspace decomposition
heat_width = com_img.shape[0] - 28 + 1
heat_height = com_img.shape[1] - 28 + 1
dffs_heat = np.zeros((heat_width, heat_height))

#to find the target object, we need a slide window to slide along this composite image.
for i in range(0, heat_width):
    for j in range(0, heat_height):
        img_x_start = i
        img_x_end = i + 28
        img_y_start = j
        img_y_end = j + 28
        img_cropped = com_img[img_x_start:img_x_end, img_y_start:img_y_end]
        residual = img_cropped - test_image1#DFFS=y-(averagex+reconstruction),using PCA representation of a MNIST number
        dffs_heat[i,j] = np.linalg.norm(residual)

d. Evaluate the performance of SSD and DFFS (i.e. illustrate when it works, and when it does not work).

Answer：

  1. The above results show that the performance of SSD is worse that DFFS. Although both of the techiques can not detect '5' perfectly, they can assist detecting number obejcts in the composite image (to some extent).
  2. It seems that the SSD perform better when recognitzing a template that the target object in the composite image almost is the same as the template. And the DFFS will reach a robust performance when the appearance of the target object change according to relative factors such as one's different writing style.
